record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 1088,
  "cap": "INFO_DISCLOSURE",
  "endpoint": "POST /api/v1/projects/:project_id/repos/test (source_kind in {local-path,local})",
  "rationale": "read_local_git_remote(path) accepts an operator-supplied filesystem path, reads `<path>/.git/config`, and returns the `[remote \"origin\"] url =` value verbatim in TestRepoResponse.on_disk_git_remote (router.rs:1008-1016, parser at :1088-1117). No root-confinement, no canonicalisation, symlinks honoured. Two primitives: (a) filesystem oracle — the three response-message variants (`path does not exist` / `is not a directory` / `path readable; no .git/config remote on disk`) discriminate file existence and directory type across the daemon's entire read-permission surface, giving an authenticated attacker a fast probe over the host filesystem; (b) credential exfiltration — any readable `.git/config` whose origin embeds basic-auth (`https://user:token@host/repo.git`) is echoed back to the caller. Note: `require_project` runs first so this needs a valid project_id, but `POST /api/v1/projects` is open to any bearer-holder and accepts arbitrary names, so the project gate is one hop, not a real barrier. Distinct from the existing PATH_TRAVERSAL finding (DELETE repo) and from the git_ls_remote SSRF finding (different code path, different sink).",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "POST /api/v1/projects/proj-x/repos/test {\"source_kind\":\"local-path\",\"source_url_or_path\":\"/home/victim/proj-with-creds\"} — response.on_disk_git_remote leaks any embedded token; iterate paths to map the filesystem via the three distinct error strings."
}

